Overview of Cypress Component Testing

01
On this page
  1. Configuration & Project Structure
    1. Test Script in package.json
    2. Webpack Configuration
    3. cypress.json Configuration
  2. Running Cypress Component Testing

Cypress Component testing is used to test at the component level, as opposed to the page level.

This is similar to how we used Jest in the previous section but there are some differences.

First off, Cypress Component Testing uses a real browser instead of jsdom. It is also more closely tied to React, Vue, and frameworks built on top of them.

Cypress Component Testing is a great choice if you have isolated components and are planning on using Cypress for integration testing. Note that the original Cypress is framework agnostic: it’s Cypress Component Testing that is tied to view rendering libraries like React & Vue.

I like to think of CCT as kind of a mix between Storybook and Jest, in a way. Being able to manually interact with a component then write automated tests and see how they run in Cypress Component Testing is pretty cool workflow.

I consulted on a project that used Cypress for integration tests. One of the app components required the application to go through several different user flows and states including modals before I could write its accessibility tests. Adding Cypress Component Testing allowed me to skip past all of that and work with only the component I needed.

Read more about Cypress Component Testing in their docs.

Configuration & Project Structure

Test Script in package.json

Cypress Component Testing is already installed in the workshop repository.

Inside of package.json is a script that starts Cypress Component Testing using the npx tool.

// inside of package.json
...
scripts: {
	...
	"test:components": "npx cypress open-ct"
}
// inside of package.json
...
scripts: {
	...
	"test:components": "npx cypress open-ct"
}

Webpack Configuration

There is a Webpack configuration for Cypress Component Testing. The file is located in the webpack.config.js file inside of the exercise2 directory.

Similar to Storybook, the configuration file loads Babel, Sass support, and loads the file for the CSS variables we use in the project.

cypress.json Configuration

There is an additional configuration for both Cypress Component Testing and “regular” Cypress located in cypress.json in the root of the directory.

Since there are different types of Cypress tests in our workshop repo, there is an entry for component as well as integrationFolder at the top level:

// cypress.json
{
	"component": {
	   "componentFolder": "exercise2-cypress-components",
	    "testFiles": "**/*test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"
	},
	"integrationFolder": "exercise3-cypress-integration",
  "testFiles": "**/*.test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
  "video": false
}
// cypress.json
{
	"component": {
	   "componentFolder": "exercise2-cypress-components",
	    "testFiles": "**/*test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"
	},
	"integrationFolder": "exercise3-cypress-integration",
  "testFiles": "**/*.test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
  "video": false
}

In both cases, the configuration file tells Cypress where to find the tests.

Running Cypress Component Testing

To start Cypress Component Testing, run yarn test:components in a terminal.

A browser window will appear with a UI showing the tests it found in the directory specified in the config file.

Clicking the meganav.test.js file in the sidebar will run the tests.

In this case, Cypress Component Testing shows that we have a failing test.

There is a brief explanation of the error, as well as a “Learn More” link that goes to the proper section of the Cypress docs.

One of the coolest features of Cypress is that we are able to click back through the steps that happened before the test failed.

Also, because it’s a browser-based tool that renders our actual component, we can use DevTools to manually inspect our component to help determine why the test might fail.

Now that we know what the UI looks like, let’s go read the test and fix the failure.
